The raisins cost $\$0.80$ per ounce.

For the second question, we know the total cost equals $\maroonD{\$1}$, but we do not know the number of ounces. We'll substitute into our original equation again.

$\begin{align}
\maroonD{\text{total price}} &= \greenD{\text{number of ounces}} \cdot \blueD{\text{price per ounce}}\\\\
\maroonD{1} &= \greenD{\text{number of ounces}} \cdot \blueD{0.8}
\end{align}$

Let's divide both sides of the equation by $\blueD{0.8}$ and solve for the number of ounces.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{\maroonD{1}}{0.8} &= \dfrac{\greenD{\text{number of ounces}} \cdot \cancel{\blueD{0.8}}}{\cancel{0.8}}\\\\
1.25&=\greenD{\text{number of ounces}}
\end{align}$

We can buy $1.25$ ounces of raisins for $\$1$.

Now we can divide both sides of the equation by $\greenD{6}$ to solve for the distance per liter.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{\maroonD{48}}{6} &= \dfrac{\cancel{\greenD{6}} \cdot \blueD{\text{distance per liter}}}{\cancel 6}\\\\
8&=\blueD{\text{distance per liter}}
\end{align}$

Amelia drove $8$ kilometers per liter.

For the second question, we know the total distance equals $\maroonD{1}$ kilometer, but we do not know the number of liters. We'll substitute into our original equation again.

$\begin{align}
\maroonD{\text{total distance}} &= \greenD{\text{number of liters}} \cdot \blueD{\text{distance per liter}}\\\\
\maroonD{1} &= \greenD{\text{number of liters}} \cdot \blueD{8}
\end{align}$

Let's divide both sides of the equation by $\blueD{8}$ and solve for the number of liters.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{\maroonD{1}}{8} &= \dfrac{\greenD{\text{number of liters}} \cdot \cancel{\blueD{8}}}{\cancel{8}}\\\\
0.125&=\greenD{\text{number of liters}}
\end{align}$

At that rate, it takes $0.125$ liters of gasoline to drive $1$ kilometer.

Now we can divide both sides of the equation by $\greenD{10}$ to solve for the growth per day.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{\maroonD{16}}{10} &= \dfrac{\cancel{\greenD{10}} \cdot \blueD{\text{growth per day}}}{\cancel{10}}\\\\
1.6&=\blueD{\text{growth per day}}
\end{align}$

The grass grows $1.6$ centimeters per day.

For the first question, we know the total growth equals $\maroonD{1}$ centimeter, but we do not know the number of days. We'll substitute into our original equation again.

$\begin{align}
\maroonD{\text{total growth}} &= \greenD{\text{number of days}} \cdot \blueD{\text{growth per day}}\\\\
\maroonD{1} &= \greenD{\text{number of days}} \cdot \blueD{1.6}
\end{align}$

Let's divide both sides of the equation by $\blueD{1.6}$ and solve for the number of days.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{\maroonD{1}}{1.6} &= \dfrac{\greenD{\text{number of days}} \cdot \cancel{\blueD{1.6}}}{\cancel{1.6}}\\\\
0.625&=\greenD{\text{number of days}}
\end{align}$

At that rate, it takes $0.625$ days for the grass to grow $1$ centimeter.

Now we can divide both sides of the equation by $\greenD{100}$ to solve for the soy sauce-to-vinegar ratio.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{\maroonD{150}}{100} &= \dfrac{\cancel{\greenD{100}} \cdot \blueD{\text{soy sauce-to-vinegar ratio}}}{\cancel{100}}\\\\
1.5&=\blueD{\text{soy sauce-to-vinegar ratio}}
\end{align}$

The soy sauce-to-vinegar ratio is $1.5$. Bonnie mixes $1.5$ milliliters of soy sauce with every $1$ milliliter of vinegar.

For the second question, we know the amount of soy sauce is $\maroonD{1}$ milliliter, but we do not know the amount of vinegar. We'll substitute into our original equation again.

$\begin{align}
\maroonD{\text{amount of soy sauce}} &= \greenD{\text{amount of vinegar}} \cdot \blueD{\text{soy sauce-to-vinegar ratio}}\\\\
\maroonD{1} &= \greenD{\text{amount of vinegar}} \cdot \blueD{1.5}
\end{align}$

Let's divide both sides of the equation by $\blueD{1.5}$ and solve for the amount of vinegar.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{\maroonD{1}}{1.5} &= \dfrac{\greenD{\text{amount of vinegar}} \cdot \cancel{\blueD{1.5}}}{\cancel{1.5}}\\\\
\dfrac{2}{3}&=\greenD{\text{amount of vinegar}}
\end{align}$

Bonnie mixes $\dfrac{2}{3}$ milliliter of vinegar with every $1$ milliliter of soy sauce.
